In [0]:
num_categories = len(df['Id'].unique())
     
print(f'Number of categories: {num_categories}')

Number of categories: 5005

There are too many categories to plot the count by category, so let's instead plot the number of categories by the number of images in that category.

In [0]:
import math
from collections import Counter

size_buckets = Counter(df['Id'].value_counts().values)

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

plt.bar(range(len(size_buckets)), list(size_buckets.values())[::-1], align='center')
plt.xticks(range(len(size_buckets)), list(size_buckets.keys())[::-1])
plt.title("Num of categories by images in the training set")

plt.show()

As we can see, the vast majority of classes only have a single image in them. This is going to make predictions very difficult for most conventional image classification models.

In [0]:
total = len(df['Id'])
print(f'Total images in training set {total}')

Total images in training set 25361
In [0]:
df['Id'].value_counts().head(3)
Out[0]:
new_whale    9664
w_23a388d      73
w_9b5109b      65
Name: Id, dtype: int64

New whale is the biggest category with9664, followed by w_23a388d. New whale is any whale that isn't in scientist's database. Since we can pick 5 potential labels per id, it's probably going to make sense to always include new_whale in our prediction set, since there's always an 38.1% chance that's the right one. Let's take a look at one of the classes, to get a sense what flute looks like from the same whale

First Trial : Using the whole dataset¶

Convert the images to arrays¶

In [0]:
def prepareImages(data, m,image_size):
    print("Preparing images")
    X_train = np.zeros((m, 100, 100, 3))
    count = 0
    
    for fig in data['Image']:
        #load images into images of size image_sizeximage_sizex3
        img = image.load_img(fig, target_size=(image_size, image_size, 3))
        img = image.img_to_array(img)
        #print(np.shape(x))
        
        img = preprocess_input(img)
        #print(np.shape(x))
        
        X_train[count] = img
        #X_train[count] = np.pad(img, ((62,62),(62,62),(0,0)), 'constant')
        if (count%500 == 0):
            print("Processing image: ", count+1, ", ", fig)
        count += 1
    
    return X_train
  
def prepare_labels(y,):
    values = np.array(y)
    label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
    label_encoder.fit(values)
    
    y = label_encoder.transform(values)
    
      
    return y,label_encoder

Second trial : Removing the new_whale samples and data augmentation for the whole set¶

Bad results ==> reconfiguration

we tuned the value of the learning rate, the number of neurons in the fully connected layers, the type of optimizer (RMS, Adam...)

  • New IDEA: the label new_whale is a majority while it doesn't add any information to the data. It is not even a class, the images in the class 'new_whale' don't have any similarity in terms of features, and in the test set if some picture looks like one of them it will get simply new_whale as label. thus we get rid of new_whale in the train set and we we put it for all the predictive labels.

## Data augmentation 
def feature_augmentation(X, y, exples_to_add ):
    # convert from int to float
    #X = X.astype('float32')

    # define data preparation
    datagen_fea = ImageDataGenerator(featurewise_center=True,
                               featurewise_std_normalization=True)
    # fit parameters from data
    datagen_fea.fit(X)
    # configure batch size and retrieve one batch of images
    for X_batch, y_batch in datagen_fea.flow(X, y, batch_size=exples_to_add):
        # create a grid of 3x3 images
        #for i in range(0, 9):
        #	plt.subplot(330 + 1 + i)
        #	plt.imshow(X_batch[i])
        # show the plot
        #plt.show()
        break
    return(X_batch, y_batch)
In [0]:
def conc(X_cleaned, y_cleaned, X_batch, y_batch):
    X_cleaned = np.concatenate((X_cleaned, X_batch), axis=0)
    y_cleaned = np.concatenate((y_cleaned, y_batch), axis=0)
    return(X_cleaned, y_cleaned)

def rotation_augmentation(X, y , exples_to_add):
    #X = X.astype('float32')
    # define data preparation
    datagen_rot = ImageDataGenerator(rotation_range=90)
    # fit parameters from data
    datagen_rot.fit(X)
    # configure batch size and retrieve one batch of images
    for X_batch, y_batch in datagen_rot.flow(X, y, batch_size =exples_to_add):
        # create a grid of 3x3 images
        #for i in range(0, 9):
        #	plt.subplot(330 + 1 + i)
        #	plt.imshow(X_batch[i])
        # show the plot
        #plt.show()
        break
    return(X_batch, y_batch)

def flip_augmentation(X, y , exples_to_add):
    #X = X.astype('float32')
    # define data preparation
    datagen_flip = ImageDataGenerator(horizontal_flip=True,
                                               vertical_flip=True)
    # fit parameters from data
    datagen_flip.fit(X)
    # configure batch size and retrieve one batch of images
    for X_batch, y_batch in datagen_flip.flow(X, y, batch_size=exples_to_add):
        # create a grid of 3x3 images
        #for i in range(0, 9):
        #	plt.subplot(330 + 1 + i)
        #	plt.imshow(X_batch[i])
        # show the plot
        #plt.show()
        break
    return(X_batch, y_batch)

def all_augmentation(X,y, exples_to_add):

    # convert from int to float
    #X= X.astype('float32')

    # define data preparation
    datagen_all = ImageDataGenerator( rotation_range=40,
                                               width_shift_range=0.2,
                                               height_shift_range=0.2,
                                               shear_range=0.2,
                                               zoom_range=0.2,
                                               fill_mode='nearest',
                                               horizontal_flip=True,
                                               vertical_flip=True)
    # fit parameters from data
    datagen_all.fit(X)
    # configure batch size and retrieve one batch of images
    for X_batch, y_batch in datagen_all.flow(X, y, batch_size=exples_to_add):
        # create a grid of 3x3 images
        #for i in range(0, 9):
        #	plt.subplot(330 + 1 + i)
        #	plt.imshow(X_batch[i])
        # show the plot
        #plt.show()
        break
    return(X_batch, y_batch)
In [0]:
def augment(X_cleaned, y_cleaned, portion_x, portion_y, exples_to_add):
  
    nb = exples_to_add // 5 
    final = exples_to_add - nb * 4 
  
    #portion_x = portion_x.astype('float32')
  
    X_batch, y_batch = feature_augmentation(portion_x,portion_y, nb)
    X_cleaned, y_cleaned = conc(X_cleaned, y_cleaned, X_batch, y_batch)
    print('After feature augmentation',X_cleaned.shape, y_cleaned.shape)
  
    X_batch_rot, y_batch_rot = rotation_augmentation(portion_x,portion_y, nb)
    X_cleaned, y_cleaned = conc(X_cleaned, y_cleaned, X_batch_rot, y_batch_rot)
    print('After rotation_augmentation ',X_cleaned.shape, y_cleaned.shape)
  
    X_batch_zoom, y_batch_zoom = zoom_augmentation(portion_x,portion_y, nb)
    X_cleaned, y_cleaned = conc(X_cleaned, y_cleaned, X_batch_zoom, y_batch_zoom)
    print('After zoom_augmentation ',X_cleaned.shape, y_cleaned.shape)
  
  
    X_batch_flip, y_batch_flip = flip_augmentation(portion_x,portion_y, nb)
    X_cleaned, y_cleaned = conc(X_cleaned, y_cleaned, X_batch, y_batch)
    print('After flip_augmentation ',X_cleaned.shape, y_cleaned.shape)
  
    X_batch_all, y_batch_all = all_augmentation(portion_x,portion_y, final)
    X_cleaned, y_cleaned = conc(X_cleaned, y_cleaned, X_batch, y_batch)
    print('After several augmentation ',X_cleaned.shape, y_cleaned.shape)
    return(X_cleaned, y_cleaned)

sum_update = 0
print(X_original.shape, y_original.shape)
for i in range(1, 2):
    portion_x = X_original[sum_update:sum_update + d[i]]
    portion_y = y_original[sum_update:sum_update + d[i]]
    sum_update += d[i] 
    X_targeted_augmentation, y_targeted_augmentation = augment(X_targeted_augmentation,y_targeted_augmentation,portion_x,portion_y, (73-i))
